The BNP in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2001|2001 general election]] saved 5 deposits (out of 33 contested seats) and secured its best ever general election result in [[Oldham West and Royton]] (which had recently been the scene of racially motivated rioting between white and Asian youths) where party leader [[Nick Griffin]] secured 16% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/dec/12/politics.race1 |title=How the BNP turned racial hatred into votes |last=Ward |first=Lucy |work=The Guardian |date=12 December 2001}}</ref>

The [[United Kingdom general election, 2005|2005 general election]] was considered a major breakthrough by the BNP, as they picked up 192,746 votes in the 119 constituencies it contested, took a 0.7% share of the overall vote, and retained a deposit in 40 of the seats.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/frontpage/4519347.stm |work=BBC News |title=BNP sees increase in total votes |date=6 May 2005 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

The BNP put forward candidates for 338 out of 650 seats for the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010 General Election]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecst.org.uk/docs/Elections%20Report%20-%20General%20Elections%202010_for%20web.pdf |title=Elections Report |publisher=Community Security Trust |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> gaining 563,743 votes<ref name="BBC National Results">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/ |work=BBC News |title=National Results |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> (1.9%), finishing in fifth place and failing to win any seats. However, a record of 73 deposits were saved. Party chairman Nick Griffin came third in the [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking]] constituency, behind [[Margaret Hodge]] of Labour and Simon Marcus of the Conservatives, who were first and second respectively. At 14.6%, this was the BNP's best result in any of the seats it contested that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/a11.stm |title=Barking |work=BBC News |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Nick Griffin, talking to voters.jpg|170px|thumb|right|[[Nick Griffin]] talking to voters in [[Romford Market]].]]

===Local elections===
{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#Local_elections|l1=British National Party election results (local elections)}}
The BNP's first electoral success came in 1993, when [[Derek Beackon]] was returned as a councillor in [[Millwall]], London. He lost his seat in elections the following year. The next BNP success in local elections was not until the [[Burnley Council election, 2002|2002]] local elections, when three BNP candidates gained seats on [[Burnley (borough)|Burnley]] council.<ref name="parliament.uk">{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snsg-05064.pdf |title=Electoral performance of the British National  Party in the UK |date=15 May 2009 |work= |publisher=Parliament |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

The party had 55 councillors for a time in 2009.<ref name="parliament.uk"/> After the [[United Kingdom local elections, 2013|2013 local county council elections]], the BNP was left with a total of two [[Borough Council|borough councillors]] in [[Local government in England|England]]:<ref>{{cite news |first=Conal |last=Urquhart |url=http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/may/04/bnp-members-breed-elections |title=BNP calls on members to breed more after elections disaster |work=The Guardian |date=4 May 2013 |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>

===London Assembly and Mayor===
BNP lead candidate [[Richard Barnbrook]] won a seat in the [[London Assembly]] in May 2008, after the party gained 5.3% of the London-wide vote.<ref name="Barn53">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7381633.stm |title=BNP wins seat in London Assembly |date=3 May 2008 |work=BBC News |accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref> However, in August 2010, he resigned the party whip and became an independent.<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Matthew |date=29 September 2010 |title=BNP expels Richard Barnbrook as bitter feud threatens to tear apart party |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/sep/29/bnp-barnbrook-expelled-griffin-feud |work=The Guardian |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

===European Parliament===
{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#European_Parliament||l1=British National Party election results (European Parliament)}}
The BNP has taken part in European Parliament elections since 1999, when they received 1.13% of the total vote (102,647 votes).

In the [[European Parliament Election, 2004 (UK)|2004 elections to the European Parliament]], the BNP won 4.9% of the vote, making it the sixth biggest party overall, but did not win any seats.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk">{{cite news |last=Wheeler |first=Brian |title=Will BNP election gains last? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4968406.stm |accessdate=12 April 2013 |work=BBC News |date=5 May 2006}}</ref>

The BNP won two seats in the European Parliament in the [[European Parliament election, 2009 (United Kingdom)|2009 elections]]. [[Andrew Brons]] was elected in the [[Yorkshire and the Humber (European Parliament constituency)|Yorkshire and the Humber]] regional constituency with 9.8% of the vote.<ref name="BBC-BNP first seat">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8088133.stm |title=Labour slumps to historic defeat |work=BBC News |date=8 June 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> Party chairman Nick Griffin was elected in the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West region]], with 8% of the vote.<ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/elections/euro/09/html/ukregion_34.stm |title=European Election 2009: North West |date=8 June 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref> Nationally, the BNP received 6.26%.

===Welsh Assembly===
{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#National_Assembly_for_Wales|l1=British National Party election results (National Assembly for Wales)}}
In the 2007 [[Welsh Assembly]] [[National Assembly for Wales election, 2007|elections]], the BNP fielded 20 candidates, four in each of the five regional lists, with [[Nick Griffin]] standing in the [[South Wales West (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|South Wales West]] region.<ref>{{cite news |title=Immigration a key issue, says BNP |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/6558981.stm |work=BBC News |date=16 April 2007 |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> It did not win any seats, but was the only minor party to have saved deposits in the electoral regions, one in the North Wales region and the other in the South Wales West region. In total the BNP polled 42,197 votes (4.3%).

In the [[National Assembly for Wales election, 2011|2011 Welsh Assembly elections]], the BNP fielded 20 candidates, four in each of the five regional lists and for the first time 7 candidates were fielded in [[First-past-the-post voting|FPTP]] constituencies. On the regional lists, the BNP polled 22,610 votes (2.4%), down 1.9% from 2007.<ref name="BBC News: Wales elections">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/constituency/html/wales.stm |title=Wales elections |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> In 2 out of the 7 FPTP constituencies contested the BNP saved desposits: ([[Swansea East (Assembly constituency)|Swansea East]] and [[Islwyn (Assembly constituency)|Islwyn]]).<ref name="BBC News: Wales elections"/>

===Scottish Parliament===
{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#Scottish_Parliament|l1=British National Party election results (Scottish Parliament)}}
In the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election]], the party fielded 32 candidates, entitling it to public funding and an election broadcast, prompting criticism.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uaf.org.uk/2007/08/no-to-public-funds-for-fascism/ |title=No to public funds for fascism |accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP received 24,616 votes (1.2%), no seats were won, nor were any deposits saved.

In the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election]], the BNP fielded 32 candidates in the regional lists. 15,580 votes were polled (0.78%).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/region/html/scotland.stm |title=Scotland elections |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref>

===Northern Ireland Assembly===
{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#Northern_Ireland_Legislative_Assembly|l1=British National Party election results (Northern Ireland Legislative Assembly)}}
The BNP fielded 3 candidates for the first time in three constituencies each in the [[Northern Ireland Assembly election, 2011|2011 Northern Ireland Legislative Assembly elections]] ([[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|Belfast East]], [[East Antrim (Assembly constituency)|East Antrim]] and [[South Antrim (Assembly constituency)|South Antrim]]). 1,252 votes were polled (0.2%), winning no seats for the party.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/constituency/html/northern_ireland.stm |title=Northern Ireland elections |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref>

==Legal issues==
===Claims of repression of free speech===
The BNP says that [[National Union of Journalists|NUJ]] guidelines on reporting 'far right' organisations forbid unionised journalists from reporting uncritically on the party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bnp.org.uk/2008/03/the-media-reporting-on-the-bnp/ |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20081211165521/http://bnp.org.uk/2008/03/the-media-reporting-on-the-bnp/ |archivedate=2008-12-11 |title=The Media: Reporting on the BNP |author=Martin Wingfield |date=16 March 2008 |accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnp.org.uk/news/national/traitors-%E2%80%93-3-denis-macshane |title=The Traitors – 3. Denis MacShane |publisher=British National Party |date=27 May 2013 |accessdate=6 September 2013}}</ref> In April 2007, an election broadcast was cancelled by [[BBC Radio Wales]] whose lawyers believed that the broadcast was defamatory of the [[Chief Constable]] of [[North Wales Police]], [[Richard Brunstrom]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2007/apr/24/thefarright.media |title=BNP forced to change election broadcast |work=The Guardian |first=Hélène |last=Mulholland |date=24 April 2007}}</ref> The BNP claimed that BBC editors were following an agenda.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20071014195731/http://www.bnp.org.uk/news_detail.php?newsId=1477 |title=BBC bans BNP election broadcast |date=24 April 2007 |publisher=British National Party |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref>

[[File:BNP Race Hate Trial.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Two suited men wave from behind a red brick wall, at the top of a short flight of steps leading to a grey building. Several police officers are in attendance.|Nick Griffin and Mark Collett leave Leeds Crown Court on 10 November 2006 after being found not guilty of charges of incitement to racial hatred at their retrial.]]

===Employment cases and related controversies===
In ''[[ASLEF v. United Kingdom]]'', the [[European Court of Human Rights]] overturned an employment appeal tribunal ruling that awarded BNP member and train driver [[Jay Lee]] damages for expulsion from a trade union. It found that the union was entitled to decide who could be a member, and that the UK was in breach of the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] in the way it had treated ASLEF.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/pages/search.aspx?i=001-79604 |title=Case of Associated Society of Locomotive Engineers & Firemen (ASLEF) v. the United Kingdom |date=27 February 2007 |publisher=European Court of Human Rights |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref>

[[Redfearn v United Kingdom|Arthur Redfearn]] was a bus driver whose BNP membership was unknown to his employer, Serco, until he was elected as a councillor. His employer was concerned that he might endanger its contract with a local authority to transport vulnerable people of various ethnicities from a day centre and he was dismissed. The Employment Tribunal held that members of racist organisations could lawfully be dismissed on health and safety grounds if there was a danger of violence occurring in the workplace.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emplaw.co.uk/lawguide?startpage=2005irlr744.htm |title=Disclaw Publishing – Employment Law, unfair dismissal, redundancy pay |publisher=Emplaw.co.uk |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> In November 2012, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] made a majority ruling (4 to 3) that in Redfearn's case against the UK government, his rights under Article 11 (free association) had been infringed,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/law/2012/nov/06/bus-driver-bnp-wins-rights-case |title=Bus driver sacked for BNP membership wins case in Strasbourg |date=6 November 2012 |publisher=The Guardian |first=Owen |last=Bowcott}}</ref> but not those under Article 10 (free expression) or Article 14 (discrimination).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/pages/search.aspx?i=001-114240 |title=CASE OF REDFEARN v. THE UNITED KINGDOM |date=6 November 2012 |publisher=European Court of Human Rights |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref>

====Organisations which ban BNP membership====
Several organisations prohibit their staff from being members of the BNP. Membership of the BNP, [[Combat 18]] and the National Front by police officers and staff was prohibited by then Home Secretary [[David Blunkett]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/the_british_national_party_26 |title=The British National Party |publisher=WhatDoTheyKnow |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> following an undercover TV exposure of racism in a police training centre.<ref>{{cite news |title=Undercover cop |author=Stuart Jeffries |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2003/oct/21/bbc.raceintheuk |work=The Guardian |date=21 October 2003 |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> The Association of Chief Police Officers banned serving police officers joining the BNP in 2004.<ref name="bettleysun">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3930175.stm |title=ACPO bans police from joining BNP |work=BBC News |date=27 July 2004 }}</ref> Simon Darby has claimed that the BNP has members who remain covert. Manchester Police Authority has viewed footage taken at BNP events in order to identify off-duty officers in attendance at a BNP St George's Day rally, wearing BNP badges and T-shirts, with the slogan "Love Britain or Fuck Off".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2007/may/12/ukcrime.thefarright |title=Inquiry into claim that police joined BNP event |work=The Guardian  |first=Matthew |last=Taylor |date=14 May 2007}}</ref> After BNP membership lists were leaked on the Internet, a number of police forces investigated officers whose names appeared on the lists.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2008/nov/19/police-bnp-far-right-list |title=Police scour BNP membership to find officers breaching ban |work=The Guardian |first=Ian |last=Cobain |date=19 November 2008}}</ref>

A ban on BNP membership for prison workers was imposed by [[Martin Narey]], Director of the Prison Service, in 2002. Narey told the BBC that he received hate mail and a death threat as a result.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4247329.stm |title='No-one wanted' top UK jails post |date=8 February 2005 |accessdate=4 April 2013 |work=BBC News}}</ref> In February 2009, the [[General Synod of the Church of England]] voted to ban its clergy from joining the BNP.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7880313.stm |title=Synod votes in favour of BNP ban |date=10 February 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> In 2010 Education Secretary [[Michael Gove]] pledged to allow head teachers to dismiss employees who are members of the BNP, saying that "I don't believe that membership of the BNP is compatible with being a teacher... allow headteachers and governing bodies the powers and confidence to be able to dismiss teachers engaging in extremist activity."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2010/11/bnp-teachers-gove-schools |title=In praise of Michael Gove: He's wrong on free schools but right to ban BNP teachers |last=Hasan |first=Medhi |work=New Statesman |date=2 November 2010 |accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.com/education/2010/nov/02/bnp-members-barred-teaching |title=BNP members to be barred from teaching |work=The Guardian |date=2 November 2010 |last=Vasagar |first=Jeevan |accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref>

===Association with violence===
John Hagan claims that the BNP has conducted [[Right-wing politics and violence|right-wing extremist violence]] in order to gain "institutionalized power".<ref name="haganwilliam">{{harvnb|Heitmeyer|2003|p=406}}</ref> Critics of the BNP, such as [[Human Rights Watch]] in a 1997 report, have asserted that the party recruits from skinhead groups and that it promotes racist violence.<ref>{{harvnb|Human Rights Watch|1997|p=13}}</ref>

In the past, Nick Griffin has defended the threat of violence to further the party's aims. In 1986, when Griffin was Deputy Chairman of the NF, he advised his audience at an anti-[[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] rally to use the "traditional British methods of the brick, the boot and the fist."<ref>{{cite news |title= |author= |url= |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=17 February 1986}}</ref> After the BNP won its first council seat in 1993, he wrote that the BNP should not be a "postmodernist rightist party" but "a strong, disciplined organisation with the ability to back up its slogan 'Defend Rights for Whites' with well-directed boots and fists. When the crunch comes, power is the product of force and will, not of rational debate". In 1997 he said: "It is more important to control the streets of a city than its council chambers."<ref name="guardng">{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/theobserver/2002/sep/01/features.magazine37 |title=Flying the flag |last=Anthony |first=Andrew |date=1 September 2002 |work=The Guardian  |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

A BBC ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' programme reported on a number of BNP members who have had criminal convictions, some racially motivated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Party Organisers: Criminal Record |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/programmes/2001/bnp_special/membership/organisers/criminal.stm |work=Under the skin of the BNP |work=BBC News |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> Some of the more notable convictions include:
* [[John Tyndall (politician)|John Tyndall]] had convictions for assault and organising paramilitary neo-Nazi activities. In 1986 he was jailed for conspiracy to publish material likely to incite racial hatred.<ref>{{harvnb|Human Rights Watch|1997|p=14}}</ref>
* In 1998, Nick Griffin was convicted of violating section 19 of the [[Public Order Act 1986]], relating to [[hate speech|incitement to racial hatred]]. He received a nine-month prison sentence, suspended for two years, and was fined £2,300.<ref name="british state">{{cite web |url=http://www.libertarian.co.uk/lapubs/legan/legan029.pdf |title=The British State versus Freedom of Expression: The Case of R. v. Griffin |author=David Botsford |publisher=Libertarian Alliance |accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>
* Joseph Owens served eight months in prison for sending razor blades in the post to Jewish people and another term for carrying CS gas and knuckledusters.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/page.cfm?objectid=12800817&method=full |title=BNP man sent razor blades to city Jews |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=2 April 2003 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>
* Colin Smith, who in 2004 was the BNP's South East London organiser, has 17 convictions for burglary, theft, possession of drugs and assaulting a police officer.<ref>{{Cite news |title=On the Le Pen menu: roast beef and raw bigotry |author=Sophie Goodchild |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/on-the-le-pen-menu-roast-beef-and-raw-bigotry-6170790.html |work=The Independent  |date=25 April 2004 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>
* [[Richard Edmonds]], at the time BNP National Organiser, was sentenced to three months in prison in 1994 for his part in a racist attack. Edmonds threw a glass at the victim as he was walking past an East London pub where a group of BNP supporters was drinking. Others then 'glassed' the man in the face and punched and kicked him as he lay on the ground, including BNP supporter Stephen O'Shea, who was jailed for 12 months. Another BNP supporter, Simon Biggs, was jailed for four and a half years for his part in the attack.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Anger as BNP chief walks free over race attack |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/anger-as-bnp-chief-walks-free-over-race-attack-1423282.html |work=The Independent |date=18 June 1994 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

====Tony Lecomber cases====
[[Tony Lecomber]] was imprisoned for three years for possessing explosives, after a [[nail bomb]] exploded while he was carrying it to the offices of the [[Workers' Revolutionary Party (UK)|Workers' Revolutionary Party]] in 1985.<ref>{{Cite news |author=John Davison, Ian Burrell and Cyril Dixon |title=Exposed: Labour trickery that hyped BNP to election victory |work=The Sunday Times |date=19 September 1993}}</ref> He was imprisoned for three years in 1991 whilst serving as the BNP's Director of Propaganda for assaulting a Jewish teacher.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/programmes/2001/bnp_special/membership/advisory/tony_lecomber.stm |title=BBC News: BNP – Under the Skin |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

====Robert Cottage case====
{{Main|Talbot Street bomb-making haul}}
In 2007, Robert Cottage, a former BNP council candidate, was sentenced to two and a half years for possession of explosives but a conspiracy charge against him was withdrawn after two juries had been unable to reach a verdict.<ref>{{cite news |title=Second jury fails to agree on BNP 'bomb' pair |author=Matthew Taylor |url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jul/13/ukcrime.thefarright |work=The Guardian |date=13 July 2007 |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref> The prosecution claimed that Cottage had plans to assassinate [[Tony Blair]] and Liberal Democrat peer [[Tony Greaves, Baron Greaves|Lord Greaves]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-BNP activist 'wanted to shoot Tony Blair' |author=Matthew Taylor |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2007/feb/13/thefarright.ukcrime |work=The Guardian |date=13 February 2007 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> The chemicals recovered by police are believed to be the largest explosives haul ever found at a house in Britain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-BNP man faces explosives charge |author=Andrew Hewitt |url=http://www.burnleycitizen.co.uk/news/951775.exbnp_man_faces_explosives_charge/ |newspaper=The Burnley and Pendle Citizen |date=4 October 2006 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

===2008 membership list leak===
On 18 November 2008, a list of over 10,000 BNP members was published by [[Wikileaks]] in breach of a court injunction.<ref name=guardian-2008-11-18>{{cite news |title=BNP membership list leaked online |author=James Sturcke, Matthew Weaver and Ian Cobain |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2008/nov/18/bnp-membership-list-leak |work=The Guardian |date=18 November 2008 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> This included names, addresses and other personal details. People on the list included prison officers (barred from BNP membership), teachers, soldiers, civil servants and members of the clergy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9808105a-b6a5-11dd-89dd-0000779fd18c.html |title=Probe into officer on BNP list |date=20 November 2008 |work=Financial Times |accessdate=12 December 2008}}</ref>

Nick Griffin claimed that any party member dismissed from employment would be able to receive substantial compensation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sacked BNP members 'could claim £10,000' |url=http://metro.co.uk/2008/11/19/sacked-bnp-members-could-claim-10000-166680/ |newspaper=Metro |date=19 November 2008 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP advised those named on the list to deny their membership and said that they would confirm that in writing if required.<ref name=leejohnbarnes>{{cite web |url=http://leejohnbarnes.blogspot.co.uk/2008/11/bnp-fake-membership-list-issues.html |title=Lee John Barnes, BNP Legal Director |publisher=Leejohnbarnes.blogspot.com |date=18 November 2008 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP claimed it contained the names of persons who had never been members of the BNP.<ref name="guardian-2008-11-18"/> The BNP's Lee Barnes claimed that the list was false.<ref name=leejohnbarnes/>

People affected by the disclosure included a DJ, Rod Lucas, who was dropped by the [[Talksport]] radio station. He said: "I am an investigative radio journalist and am a member of over 20 political parties and pressure groups&nbsp;... It doesn't necessarily mean I agree with their views."<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3484612/Rod-Lucas-dropped-by-TalkSPORT-after-BNP-links-emerge.html |title=Rod Lucas dropped by TalkSPORT after BNP links emerge |date=19 November 2008 |accessdate= 2 April 2013 |work=The Daily Telegraph  }}</ref> A drama teacher at a prep school whose name was found on the list had been dismissed from a previous position as a result of her BNP membership.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Neil |last=Sears |title=Teacher at prestigious prep school faces probe after her former job with BNP is exposed |work=Daily Mail  |accessdate=2 April 2013 |date=22 November 2008 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1088392/Teacher-prestigious-prep-school-faces-probe-job-BNP-exposed.html}}</ref>

Following an investigation by Welsh police and the [[Information Commissioner's Office (UK)|Information Commissioner's Office]], two people were arrested in December 2008 for breach of the [[Data Protection Act]] concerning the leak.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2008/dec/05/bnp-leak-arrests |title=Two held over BNP membership leak |work=The Guardian  |date=5 December 2008 |first=Angela |last=Balakrishnan |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> Matthew Single was subsequently found guilty and fined £200. The fine was criticised as an "an absolute disgrace" by a BNP spokesman and a detective sergeant involved said he was "disappointed" with the outcome.<ref name="manfined">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/nottinghamshire/8231475.stm |title=Ex-BNP man fined over names leak |accessdate=2 April 2013 |date=1 September 2009 |work=BBC News}}</ref>

===Equality and Human Rights Commission===
The [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]] sent the BNP a letter in 2009, ahead of legal action, setting out concerns about the BNP's constitution and membership criteria. It alleged that the BNP's constitution restricting membership to white people was unlawful under the Race Relations Act. The BNP chose to fight this opinion in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]]. The Commission issued county court proceedings against party leader Nick Griffin and two other officials.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/news/2009/august/commission-issues-county-court-proceedings-against-the-bnp/ |title=Commission issues county court proceedings against the BNP |date=24 August 2009 |publisher=Equality and Human Rights Commission |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

The conclusion of the case in October 2009 saw costs awarded against the BNP.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/news/2009/october/commission-forces-bnp-to-change-its-constitution-and-membership-criteria-after-legal-case-victory/ |title=Commission forces BNP to change its constitution and membership criteria after legal case victory |date=15 October 2009 |publisher=Equality and Human Rights Commission |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP stated that Griffin was "required in Brussels" on that day. Griffin had written to BNP members preparing to concede the case because it would be too expensive to fight<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b947072a-98aa-11de-aa1b-00144feabdc0.html |title=UK – BNP's 'whites-only' rule set to be axed |work=Financial Times  |date=3 September 2009 |accessdate=23 October 2009}}</ref> and would "strip the party of the ability to fight the next general election".<ref name="timesnonwhites" /> Griffin subsequently announced that he would ask BNP members to accept the court's decision and allow non-whites to join the party,<ref name="timesnonwhites">{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6820847.ece |title=British National Party forced to admit non-whites |work=The Times  |accessdate=15 October 2009 |date=4 September 2009 |first=Fiona |last=Hamilton}}{{subscription required}}</ref> claiming that this action "outflanked" the EHRC.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/bnp-may-have-to-admit-black-and-asian-members-after-court-challenge-1803635.html |work=The Independent  |title=BNP may have to admit black and Asian members after court challenge |date=16 October 2009 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP anticipated that its members would accept the change on financial grounds.<ref name="dailymail.co.uk">{{Cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1220565/BNP-change-whites-membership-rules-fall-foul-discrimination-laws.html |title=BNP to change 'whites only' membership rules so as not to fall foul of discrimination laws |work=Daily Mail  |date=15 October 2009 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

The BNP agreed to suspend further membership applications until an Extraordinary General Meeting in January 2010 confirming changes to the constitution. The case was adjourned in order to ensure compliance.<ref name="dailymail.co.uk" /> As a result of the case, the Secretary of State for Wales, [[Peter Hain]] protested against the BBC's inclusion of Griffin on the [[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]] programme, claiming the court case meant the BNP was "an unlawful body". [[Shami Chakrabarti]], director of [[Liberty (pressure group)|Liberty]], said: "A shiny new constitution does not a democratic party make. It would be a pyrrhic victory, to say the least, if anyone thought that giving the BNP a facelift would make the slightest difference to a body with so much racism and hatred pumping through its veins."<ref name="dailymail.co.uk"/>

The courts declared that the new constitution still breached equality laws and was still indirectly discriminatory. Judge Paul Collins ordered the BNP to pay costs and said its membership list must remain "closed" until it complied with race relations laws. The BNP claimed that it had a waiting list of black and Asian people and wanted more applications from ethnic minorities.<ref name="New BNP rules rejected by court">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8564742.stm |work=BBC News |title=New BNP rules rejected by court |date=12 March 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

In November 2010, the BNP leadership was accused of lying over the matter by the EHRC who claimed that the offending passage had not been removed but merely altered.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/nov/08/nick-griffin-high-court-bnp  |work=The Guardian  |first=Matthew |last=Taylor |title=BNP leader Nick Griffin accused of lying over party's constitution |date=8 November 2010}}</ref> In a subsequent hearing the BNP leadership was found not guilty of the contempt of court. The EHRC said: "Eighteen months and seven court hearings later Mr Griffin has finally amended the constitution to bring it in line with what the Commission had originally requested."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/bnps-nick-griffin-defeats-contempt-legal-bid-2162992.html  |work=The Independent  |first1=John |last1=Aston |title=BNP's Nick Griffin defeats contempt legal bid |date=17 December 2010 }}</ref> Griffin said: "This is a great day, because the British National Party has won a spectacular [[David and Goliath]] victory".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/video/2010/dec/17/bnp-nick-griffin-legal-penalties-video  |work=The Guardian |title=BNP leader Nick Griffin avoids legal penalties |date=17 December 2010}}</ref>

==Opposition==
Amongst the most visible and vocal opponents of the BNP are [[Unite Against Fascism]] (UAF) and the magazine ''[[Searchlight (magazine)|Searchlight]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnp.org.uk/resource/searchlight%E2%80%99s-carbon-copy-plan |title=Searchlight’s Carbon Copy Plan |publisher=British National Party |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref><ref name="1June2013">{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2013/jun/01/bnp-anti-fascists-london |author=Colin Urquart |work=The Gaurdian |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=14 September 2013 |title=BNP and anti-fascists scuffle in London}}</ref> High-ranking politicians from each of the main parties have, at various times, called for their own supporters to vote for anyone but the BNP.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2006/apr/18/localelections2006.uk |title=Guardian: Cameron: vote for anyone but BNP |work=The Guardian  |date=18 April 2006 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |work=The Daily Telegraph  |title=Blair admits 'paying penalty' for US links |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1541686/Blair-admits-paying-penalty-for-US-links.html |accessdate=2 April 2013 |first=George |last=Jones |date=6 February 2007}}</ref> In 2008, then Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] stated: "Londoners and the rest of the British people know that backing the BNP is totally at odds with what it really means to be British—and the great British values the rest of us share, such as democracy and decency, freedom and fairness, tolerance and equality."<ref name="Brown">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/hope-not-hate-vote-for-equality-305140 |title=Hope not hate: Vote for equality, freedom and hope |date=29 April 2008 |work=Daily Mirror |accessdate=2 Apriil 2013}}</ref> The British Government announced in 2009 that the BNP's two MEPs would be denied some of the access and information afforded to other MEPs. The BNP would be subject to the "same general principles governing official impartiality" and they would receive "standard written briefings as appropriate from time to time", but diplomats would not be "proactive" in dealing with the BNP MEPs and that any requests for policy briefings from them would be treated differently and on a discretionary basis.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2009/jul/09/diplomats-shun-nick-griffin-bnp-europe |title= UK diplomats shun BNP officials in Europe |accessdate=1 April 2013  |first=Ian |last=Traynor |date=9 July 2009 |work=The Guardian }}</ref>

Some opponents of fascism call for no coverage to be given to groups or individuals enunciating what they describe as "[[hate speech]]". The "[[No Platform]]" stance is to deny perceived fascist hate speech any sort of publicity. The policy is most commonly associated with university student unions and debating societies,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nusconnect.org.uk/blogs/blog/aaronporter/2010/09/14/Re-affirming-our-support-for-No-Platform/ |title=Re-affirming our support for No Platform |last1=Porter |first1=Aaron |publisher=National Union of Students |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> but has also resulted in BNP candidates being banned from speaking at various hustings meetings around the country. In 2005, an invitation to Nick Griffin by the [[University of St Andrews]] Union Debating Society to participate in a debate on multiculturalism was withdrawn after protests.<ref>{{cite news |title=University's invitation to BNP leader withdrawn |author= |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/education/university-s-invitation-to-bnp-leader-withdrawn-1-674092 |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=5 February 2005 |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

===Veterans and Second World War===
In June 2009, the [[Royal British Legion]] wrote to Griffin privately to ask him to stop wearing their poppy symbol. After he refused and wore the badge at campaign events and on the party's televised election broadcast, the Legion said in an open letter: "True valour deserves respect regardless of a person's ethnic origin, and everyone who serves or has served their country deserves nothing less&nbsp;... [our national chairman] appealed to your sense of honour. But you have responded by continuing to wear the poppy. So now we're no longer asking you privately. Stop it, Mr Griffin. Just stop it."<ref>{{cite news |title=Royal British Legion tell Nick Griffin to stop wearing poppy badge |author=Matthew Taylor |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2009/jun/13/royal-british-legion-nick-griffin |work=The Guardian |date=13 June 2009 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> In September 2009, the Legion accepted a donation which it had initially rejected from BNP member Rachel Firth. Firth had spent 24 hours raising the money, half of which was given to the Legion and the other half to the BNP. The Legion said that Firth had assured them that the donation would not be exploited politically although the story was later "splashed across" the BNP's website. BNP spokesman Simon Darby denied that the party exploited the story.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8250086.stm |title=British Legion accepts BNP gift |last=Furlong |first=Ray |date=11 September 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

[[Winston Churchill]]'s family has criticised the BNP after the party used his image and quotes from one of his speeches in its campaign. Churchill's grandson, [[Nicholas Soames]], described the BNP as "monstrous" and said its use of Churchill was "offensive and disgusting".<ref>{{cite news |title=BNP's Churchill use 'disgusting' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8068717.stm |work=BBC News |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

The BNP was also caught up in a dispute with 1940s singer [[Vera Lynn]] after she objected to the party selling copies of her [[(There'll Be Bluebirds Over) The White Cliffs of Dover|White Cliffs of Dover]] CD on its website to fund its European election campaign.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dame Vera Lynn takes on BNP over White Cliffs of Dover |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/4687730/Dame-Vera-Lynn-takes-on-BNP-over-White-Cliffs-of-Dover.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=18 February 2009 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

===Violent opposition===
In the wake of the [[death of Lee Rigby]], protests and counter-protests between BNP supporters and [[Unite Against Fascism]] campaigners in London. 58 people were arrested, all UAF protesters,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22739189 |title=Fifty-eight arrested during Westminster protests |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=7 September 2013 |work=BBC News}}</ref> and at least one man, a BNP activist, was injured.<ref name="1June2013"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2334312/Anti-fascist-protestors-arrested-packed-London-buses-following-violent-clashes-BNP-outside-Parliament.html |date=1 June 2013 |title=Anti-fascist protestors arrested and packed onto London buses following violent clashes with BNP outside Parliament |last1=Rush |first1=James |last2=Bond |first2=Anthony |work=Daily Mail |accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/06/01/bnp-westminster-rally_n_3371451.html |title=BNP Westminster Protesters Clash With Rival Anti-Fascists |last=Vale |first=Paul |work=Huffington Post |date=1 June 2013 |accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>

==Online presence==
In September 2007, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' newspaper reported that [[Hitwise]], the online competitive intelligence service, said that the BNP website had more hits than any other website of a British political party.<ref>{{cite news |title=BNP website is the most popular in politics |author=Christopher Hope |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1562960/BNP-website-is-the-most-popular-in-politics.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=13 Sep 2007 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> In 2009, the party's website came under fire after it was revealed that much of the merchandise it sold was made in [[Honduras]], contrary to the party's pledge of "British Jobs for British Workers".<ref>{{cite news |title=Party called 'hypocrites' over website merchandise |author=Victoria Richards |url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/posts/view/99690/Party-called-hypocrites-over-website-merchandise/ |newspaper=Daily Star |date=21 September 2009 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

==Affiliated organisations==
===Officially linked organisations===
* The short-lived [[American Friends of the British National Party]] gave financial assistance to the BNP from American supporters, and it also facilitated contact between far right figures in both countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=American Friends of the British National Party |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/jun/12/holocaust-museum-killing-bnp |publisher=The Guardian  |date=12 June 2009 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>
* The Trafalgar Club is a dinner club for BNP supporters that does not require BNP membership.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/file_on_4/7239316.stm |work=BBC News |title=New concerns over BNP finances |date=12 February 2008 |accessdate=6 September 2013 |first=Fran |last=Abrams}}</ref>
* Albion Life Insurance was set up in September 2006 as an insurance brokerage company on behalf of the BNP, in order to raise funds for its activities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-151726902.html |title=BNP sets up life firm, ''Highbeam'' |publisher=HighBeam Research |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The firm ceased to operate in November 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searchlightmagazine.com/index.php?link=template&story=185 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061205192653/http://www.searchlightmagazine.com/index.php?link=template&story=185 |archivedate=2006-12-05 |title=A finger in too many pies |date=November 2006 |work=Searchlight |publisher=Wayback Machine |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>
* The BNP obtains some of its funding from the sale of books and heraldic or Norse jewellery. The merchandising arm of the British National Party is the Excalibur brand.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnp.org.uk/news/new-british-national-party-logo-merchandise-excalibur |title=New British National Party Logo Merchandise at Excalibur |publisher=British National Party |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref>
* ProFam was launched in 2012, as a resource for communities to make a stand against Muslim and Asian grooming gangs against vulnerable children<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnp.org.uk/news/national/profam-protecting-family |title=ProFam-Protecting the Family |publisher=British National Party |date=1 October 2012 |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref>
* [[Solidarity – The Union for British Workers]] in 2007 had 100,000 leaflets distributed by the BNP.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solidaritytradeunion.org/news-mainmenu-52/9-news4.html|title=Solidarity 100,000 Leaflet Advert|publisher=Solidarity |date=27 April 2007 |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/news/article/347/bnp-trade-union-unmasked |title=BNP trade union unmasked |work=Searchlight |publisher=Hopenothate |date=24 January 2006 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>
* The [[Christian Council of Britain]] was set up by BNP members and supporters to organise Christians "in defence of traditional Christian values". The moderator of the organisation is currently BNP member Reverend Robert West.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lincolnshire/4771779.stm |title=Suspended councillor moves to BNP |date=15 May 2006 |accessdate=22 September 2013 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnp.org.uk/news/bring-our-boys-home-petition-handed-number-10 |title=Bring Our Boys Home Petition Handed In to Number 10 |publisher=British National Party |accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref> The CCB has claimed that the Bible justifies its support for the BNP’s repatriation policy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.churchofengland.org/media-centre/news/2006/04/pr3306a.aspx|title=Christain Council of Britain |date=5 April 2006 |accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref> The [[United Reformed Church]] has said that support for organisations such as the BNP is incompatible with Christianity.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2006/apr/16/uk.localgovernment |title=Jamie Doward: "BNP link to new campaign groups" |date=16 April 2006 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=20 April 2013 }}</ref>

===International political contacts===
The BNP and the French [[National Front (France)|National Front]] have co-operated on numerous occasions. [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]] visited the UK in 2004 to assist in launching the BNP's European Parliament campaign and Nick Griffin repaid the favour by sending a delegation of BNP officials to the FN's annual 'First of May [[Joan of Arc]] parade' in Paris in 2006.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3654941.stm |title=BBC News: Le Pen UK visit sparks protests |date=25 April 2004 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP has links with the [[National Democratic Party of Germany]]. Griffin addressed an NPD rally in August 2002 headed by [[Udo Voigt]], who [[Gerhard Schroeder]] accused of trying to remove immigrants from eastern Germany. In the run-up to the [[European Parliament election, 2004 (Sweden)|2004 European Parliament election campaign]], Nick Griffin visited Sweden to give the [[National Democrats (Sweden)|National Democrat]] party his endorsement.

In London on 16 May 2008, Nick Griffin met leaders of the Hungarian far right party [[Jobbik]] to discuss co-operation between the two parties. Griffin spoke at a Jobbik party rally in August 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Top Euro Nazi's hate site run from terraced house&nbsp;... in Gravesend |author=Tom Wells |url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/1911033/Top-Euro-Nazi-Zoltan-Fuzessys-hate-site-run-from-terraced-house-in-Gravesend.html |newspaper=The Sun |date=10 November 2008 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> In April 2009, [[Simon Darby]], deputy chairman of the BNP, was welcomed with fascist salutes by members of the Italian nationalist [[Forza Nuova]] during a trip to Milan. Darby stated that the BNP would look to form an alliance with France's Front National in the European Parliament,<ref>{{cite news |title=Griffin tries to build extremist bloc in Europe |author=Jerome Taylor |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/griffin-tries-to-build-extremist-bloc-in-europe-1700174.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=9 June 2009 |accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>

The [[Alliance of European National Movements]] (AENM) was formed in [[Budapest]] on 24 October 2009 by a number of nationalist and far-right parties from countries in [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Far-right European parties forge alliance |url=http://www.eubusiness.com/news-eu/politics-parties.13f |publisher=EUbusiness |date=25 October 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnp.org.uk/news/alliance-european-national-movements-expands-9-parties |title=Alliance of European National Movements Expands to 9 Parties |accessdate=15 September 2013 |publisher=British National Party}}</ref>

===Breakaway parties and pressure groups===
*The [[New Nationalist Party (UK)|New Nationalist Party]] was formed by [[Sharon Ebanks]] on 11 December 2006, lasting for 12 months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nnp.org.uk/ |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080428235054/http://www.nnp.org.uk/ |archivedate=2008-04-28 |title=Statement by Sharon Ebanks |publisher=New Nationalist Party |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>

*In late 2010, the [[British Freedom Party]], was formed by disillusioned members of the BNP, but after failing to submit a legally required annual return to the Electoral Commission by 31 October 2012, the party was deregistered.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.searchlightmagazine.com/blogs/searchlight-blog/british-freedom-party-deregistration-the-truth-%E2%80%93-exclusive |publisher=Searchlight |title=British Freedom Party deregistration: the truth – exclusive |last=Gable |first=Sonia |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref>

*In 2011, [[Britain First]], a campaign group started by the former councillor Paul Golding, fundraiser Jim Dowson and the former South East regional organiser Andy McBride, launched the [[National Peoples Party (UK)|National People's Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britainfirst.org/about-us/people/ |title=The Britain First Leadership Team |publisher=Britain First |date=21 November 2011 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britainfirst.org/britain-first/national-peoples-party-authorised-by-electoral-commission/ |title=National People's Party official public launch |publisher=Britain First |date=21 November 2011 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

*In December 2012, [[Patria Party (UK)|Patria]] was launched by another group of former BNP activists, lead by Ian Johnson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.patria-uk.org/who-we-are/ |title=Who We Are |publisher=Patria |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>

*On 9 February 2013, former party members including [[Andrew Brons]] launched the [[British Democratic Party (2013)|British Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Neo-Nazi former BNP members launch new far-right party |author=Matthew Collins |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/02/neo-nazi-former-bnp-members-launch-new-far-right-party |newspaper=New Statesman |date=8 February 2013 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://britishdemocraticparty.co.uk/news/british-democratic-party-launches-in-leicester/ |title=British Democratic Party launches in Leicester |date=10 February 2013 |publisher=British Democratic Party |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>

